Meet organizational needs;


            Interchange Canada assignments are free from conflict of interest and political influence;
            An employee-employer relationship does not develop between the Interchange Canada participant and the host organization;

              The indeterminate status of employees under the 
              Public Service Employment Act
               is protected for the duration of the employeesâ participation in an outgoing Interchange Canada assignment;

            Consideration is given to diversity and inclusion; and

              Authority for each of the following is reflected in the departmental instrument of delegation of authority:



Assignment extensions up to a maximum of two additional years beyond the three-year assignment period; 

Waiving the requirement that participants must have been employees of the sponsoring organization, including a personal corporation, for a period of at least six months prior to the commencement of the assignment;

Assignments of incoming participants employed and sponsored by a personal corporation;

Payments to the sponsoring organization where the salary of incoming participant will exceed 125% of the total compensation that would be paid to an employee of the core public administration performing similar work;

Waiving any or all provisions of the National Joint Councilâs Foreign Service Directives (FSD) if the employee wishes to proceed with an assignment outside Canada without these entitlements, in accordance with FSDÂ 3;

Refunding less than the full amount of the participantâs salary, employer-paid benefits, and/or relocation costs; and


                  Providing relocation assistance for Interchange assignments of less than one year for executives, despite section 1.4 of the National Joint Council 
                  Relocation Directive
                  .

Only the responsible deputy head may authorize the following:


  On an exceptional basis, assignments of more than one year where the incoming participant does not meet the language requirements for the duties they will be performing;
  Waiving a participantâs two-year waiting period between Interchange assignments.

With regard to administering term employment and conversion to indeterminate status provided for in subsectionÂ 4.1.17, deputy heads are responsible for:



    Ensuring that if an employee has been employed in the organization for one or more specified terms for a cumulative period of 3Â years without a break in service longer than 60Â consecutive calendar days, the employee is converted to indeterminate status at the level of the employeeâs term position, in accordance with sectionÂ 59 of the 
    Public Service Employment Act
